    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941464693\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To gauge, how big is this binary? Are we talking ~30M or something more like ~1M? Given that this is included in the CLI uncompressed it might be reasonable to try to apply simple size optimizations where possible if it's extra large.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579749682,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773678152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941477344\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To me defaulting to localhost feels more natural, but at the same time if doing so we should probably have the option to handle both 0.0.0.0 and localhost. Maybe the <code>gdbstub_port</code> option is renamed to just <code>gdbstub</code>, and then internally the wasm does parsing to figure out if it's a port or port-and-address?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579749683,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773678152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941468458\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Instead of pulling in <code>structopt</code>, can you use <code>clap</code>? They should be pretty similar and easy to transition between, but my impression is that <code>structopt</code> is more-or-less deprecated in favor of <code>clap</code></p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579749687,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773678153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941478825\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To avoid <code>.to_vec()</code> on a big thing, could the field in <code>RunCommand</code> change to <code>&amp;'static [u8]</code>?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579749688,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773678153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941458218\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hm ok here's a sticking point I didn't realize: this makes the <code>wasmtime-cli</code> crate non-publishable because there's a dependency on something that doesn't exist on <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>. I'm also realizing now that it's not as simple as publishing this crate since it's fundamentally not publishable, it relies on being part of this workspace to build a sibling crate, which isn't present when built as a dep from <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>.</p>\n<p>The \"true fix\" for this is <a href=\"https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/cargo/reference/unstable.html#artifact-dependencies\">https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/cargo/reference/unstable.html#artifact-dependencies</a>, an unstable Cargo feature. Unfortunately we can't rely on that even in a nightly-conditional context I believe, if we tried to use that it would mean that Wasmtime would always require nightly.</p>\n<p>Some possible ideas:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Check in the gdbstub binary and verify it's built in CI. I suspect it's a bit large and will receive many changes, so not my first choice.</li>\n<li>Download gdbstub from github releases for released wasmtime-cli artifacts. We don't currently have HTTP/network dependencies in the CLI outside of WASI impls, so that'll be hard.</li>\n<li>Publish this crate to <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>, but handle failures in the <code>build.rs</code> script. That'd mean that the gdbstub binary would have to be an off-by-default optional feature which we enable for our release builds but would be off-by-default for <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Well, \"some possible ideas\" aka I think randomly in real time until something semi-reasonable pops out... Maybe that last one?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579749690,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773678153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#issuecomment-4068943997\">commented</a> on <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771\">PR #12771</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also, to clarify, @cfallin what depth would you like me to review the gdbstub component code itself? I'm happy more-or-less not reviewing it at all in the sense that it's well-sequestered, low-risk, and we'll likely iterate a lot on it in-tree. If you'd prefer though I could give it a closer look in any particular areas of interest.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579749983,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773678227
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cfallin submitted <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#pullrequestreview-3955450910\">PR review</a>.</p>",
        "id": 579761611,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773681526
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cfallin created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941805490\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Oh, hmm, I definitely didn't foresee this one being a problem either!</p>\n<p>Question on the last option: what do you mean by \"handle failures in <code>build.rs</code>\"; in other words, why would such a failure be any different than some other build failure for a crate on <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a> (some of which are e.g. crates that wrap C code and use <code>cc</code>, or do other build-time shenanigans)?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579761615,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773681527
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cfallin <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#issuecomment-4069308732\">commented</a> on <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771\">PR #12771</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also, to clarify, @cfallin what depth would you like me to review the gdbstub component code itself? I'm happy more-or-less not reviewing it at all in the sense that it's well-sequestered, low-risk, and we'll likely iterate a lot on it in-tree. If you'd prefer though I could give it a closer look in any particular areas of interest.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I guess my default answer is \"to whatever extent allows us to fulfill policy and be comfortable having this code in-repo\" :-) I agree that since it's sandboxed, the bar <em>could</em> be lower than for core runtime code. I guess the spirit of our code-review policies is still that someone should give it a once-over -- but up to you how deep you take that!</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579761873,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773681611
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton submitted <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#pullrequestreview-3955636910\">PR review</a>.</p>",
        "id": 579767813,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773683508
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941986497\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Sort of two things: </p>\n<ol>\n<li>I forget what cwd is used for <code>build.rs</code> so I don't know what effect <code>cargo build -p thing</code> will have when something is published to <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>. If that tries to build other random crates in a workspace, for example, I think that'd be bad.</li>\n<li>I think this would ideally have a better error message than \"package <code>thing</code> not found\" when built from <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>, aka something like \"you can't enable the gdbstub component when wasmtime is built from <a href=\"http://crates.io\">crates.io</a>\" or similar.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Basically, yeah, build-time weirdness is expected, but I'd like to ideally tame it. Another example would be printing a better error if <code>wasm32-wasip2</code> weren't installed, but rustc does a decent job of this already.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579767817,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773683509
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton submitted <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#pullrequestreview-3955648768\">PR review</a>.</p>",
        "id": 579770406,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773684316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2941998608\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I forget what QEMU does, but this might be a reasonable place to print \"Hey I'm listening on address A.B.C.D:XXXX for a debugger\" both to signify that's why the process is halted and also be a sort of \"join point\" for \"if you're a test, now's when you can make your TCP connection\" synchronization point.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579770408,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773684317
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2942027714\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Question for you: how come these aren't implemented with blocking I/O? My rough assumption is that blocking I/O is expected while gdbstub is doing stuff and the guest is halted, and the only async-y bit is \"wait for I/O on the TCP connection or the guest to hit an event\"</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579770409,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773684317
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2942045052\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Could this perhaps support dual setting breakpoints on mapped addresses and seeing breakpoints on raw addresses in the code section?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579770410,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773684317
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2942038591\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>stray debugging annotation?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579770411,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1773684317
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12771#discussion_r2942007457\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This may want to print something about an error perhaps? Otherwise the guest is still running and it may be \"violently deleted\" when dropping</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 579770413,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
